et tamen... ε the argument is—and in- deed Cleanthes, does not even console philosophers in all cases, for they may well be in grief at times because they have not yet attained to perfect wisdom and, as Cleanthes would admit that this is a real evil (since the assertion that it is so is one of his leading doctrines), his consolation. which consists in denying that the thing grieved about is an evil, cannot be applied. In 28, 68 it is said that philosophers do not grieve on this point, but Cic. is there thinking of Stoics, and here he is speaking more generally, as the ref. to Alcibiades shows; there, too, he speaks of philosophi summi, while those here referred to might have made but slight progress.
